You said:
authorization will happen at the very starting satage.....so we dint need authorization in bettween know....?
ChatGPT said:
Excellent observation â€” and you're on the right track conceptually. Let's clarify this precisely so you understand when and why authorization is still relevant after login.

âœ… Yes: Authorization Happens at the Start (Login Stage)
When a user logs in via:

POST /api/auth/login
ğŸ‘‰ You validate their credentials and issue a JWT token.

This JWT includes:

The user's identity (username)

Their role (USER, ADMIN)

Expiration time

Maybe userId

Once the frontend stores the token, they attach it to every request via the Authorization: Bearer <token> header.

â—BUT: Why You Still Need Authorization on Every Request
The backend is stateless. It does not remember that the user is "already authenticated."

ğŸ” Every request must prove "Who are you?" and "Are you allowed?"

Thatâ€™s why:

The JWT token must be sent every time

Your filter (JwtAuthenticationFilter) runs on every request

It extracts the user identity from the token and loads it into the security context

ğŸ”„ Flow in a Real Request
Letâ€™s say the frontend does:

GET /api/complaints
Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9...
Hereâ€™s what happens:

JwtAuthenticationFilter intercepts the request

It extracts and validates the JWT

Loads UserDetails into Spring Security context

Your controller now has the user authenticated

Now you can access:

Authentication auth = SecurityContextHolder.getContext().getAuthentication();
String username = auth.getName();
ğŸ’¡ You donâ€™t need to "authorize again" manually â€” but you must ensure the filter and Spring Security handle it per request.

ğŸ§  So in Simple Terms:
Question	Answer
Is login/authorization done once?	âœ… Login is done once per session
Do we need to re-authenticate every request?	âŒ Not manually, but JWT must be re-validated
Is authorization needed after login?	âœ… Yes, on every request (via JWT + roles)
Can backend "remember" the user?	âŒ Not in stateless REST APIs
ğŸ” Why this is Good (Stateless APIs)
Scales easily (no server session)

Works with any frontend (React, mobile, etc.)

Decouples auth from backend state

âœ… In Summary:
Yes, login happens at the start â€” but authorization is enforced on every request automatically via the token. You just donâ€™t write the logic manually every time because Spring Security + JWT Filter handles it for you behind the scenes.

